  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting requirements\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal offense\n- Established penalties for laundering financial transactions\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced AML regulations\n- Increased reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Strengthened information sharing between financial institutions\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering Act (2020)\n- Updated and expanded previous regulations\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n- Expanded scope of reporting and compliance\n\nThese laws generally:\n- Require financial institutions to implement compliance programs\n- Mandate reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Establish criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n- Create frameworks for investigating and prosecuting financial crimes\n\nInternationally, organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) develop global standards and recommendations for combating money laundering.\n\nSpecific penalties can include significant fines, asset seizure, and criminal prosecution.",
